---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="The Science of Thermally Broken Windows"
  description="How do thermally broken aluminium windows work? An in-depth explanation of thermal bridging, polyamide breaks, U-values, condensation, and energy performance."
  currentPage="science"
>

  <!-- Page header -->
  <section style="padding: 80px 0 48px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border)">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="section-label">The Science</p>
      <h1 class="section-heading">How Thermally Broken<br />Windows Work</h1>
      <p class="section-sub">A genuine explanation of the engineering behind thermally broken aluminium windows — why they perform, what makes them different, and why it matters for your home.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Main content -->
  <section>
    <div class="container" style="max-width: 860px">

      <!-- Intro -->
      <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-bottom: 64px">
        <h3>The Short Version</h3>
        <p>Standard aluminium conducts heat extremely efficiently — which is terrible for a window frame. A thermally broken frame inserts a non-conductive polyamide strip through the middle of the aluminium, physically interrupting that heat flow. The result is a frame that's warm on the inside in winter, cool on the inside in summer, and dramatically more energy efficient than standard aluminium.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 1 -->
      <div class="science-section">
        <h2>The Problem: Thermal Bridging</h2>
        <p>To understand thermally broken windows, you first need to understand the problem they solve: <strong style="color: var(--text)">thermal bridging</strong>.</p>
        <p>A thermal bridge is any material in a building's envelope that conducts heat more readily than the surrounding insulation. Aluminium is one of the most thermally conductive materials used in construction — it transfers heat approximately 1,000 times more efficiently than timber and around 10,000 times more than standard double-glazing insulation.</p>
        <p>In a standard aluminium window frame, heat flows freely from the outside of the frame straight through to the inside. In summer, your hot exterior frame transfers that heat indoors. In winter, your warm indoor air loses heat to the cold exterior frame. The glass may be well-insulated with double glazing, but the frame itself acts as a thermal bypass — a direct pipe for energy loss.</p>
        <p>This is why homes with old single-pane aluminium windows feel cold near the windows in winter even when the heating is running. The frame itself is pulling heat out of the room.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 2 -->
      <div class="science-section">
        <h2>The Solution: The Thermal Break</h2>
        <p>A thermally broken window frame solves this by physically interrupting the aluminium with a non-conductive material — typically a glass-fibre reinforced polyamide (nylon) strip, sometimes called the <strong style="color: var(--text)">thermal break</strong> or <strong style="color: var(--text)">isolator</strong>.</p>
        <p>The manufacturing process involves extruding two separate aluminium sections — an inner frame and an outer frame — and then mechanically joining them using the polyamide strips under pressure. The strips are shaped to interlock with grooves in both aluminium sections and are crimped or rolled into place, creating a permanent, structural bond.</p>
        <p>The result is a frame that has:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>An outer aluminium section exposed to the weather</li>
          <li>A polyamide thermal break (typically 14–34mm wide depending on performance grade)</li>
          <li>An inner aluminium section facing the interior</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Because polyamide has a thermal conductivity of approximately 0.3 W/(m·K) compared to aluminium's 160 W/(m·K), the break reduces the effective thermal conductivity of the frame by a factor of over 500. Heat simply cannot flow efficiently across the break.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 3 -->
      <div class="science-section">
        <h2>U-Values: Measuring Thermal Performance</h2>
        <p>The thermal performance of a window is expressed as a <strong style="color: var(--text)">U-value</strong> (also called the heat transfer coefficient), measured in W/(m²·K). It represents how much heat flows through one square metre of the window for every one degree of temperature difference between inside and outside.</p>
        <p><strong style="color: var(--text)">Lower U-value = better insulation.</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Single-pane aluminium window: U ≈ 5.0–6.0 W/(m²·K)</li>
          <li>Standard double-glazed aluminium: U ≈ 3.5–4.0 W/(m²·K)</li>
          <li>Thermally broken double-glazed: U ≈ 1.8–2.8 W/(m²·K)</li>
          <li>High-performance thermally broken with low-e: U ≈ 1.0–1.5 W/(m²·K)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The National Construction Code (NCC) sets minimum energy efficiency requirements for glazing in Australian homes. Depending on climate zone, thermally broken double glazing will often meet or exceed those requirements with headroom to spare — meaning your home is not just code-compliant but genuinely comfortable.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 4 -->
      <div class="science-section">
        <h2>Condensation: Why Cold Frames Are a Problem</h2>
        <p>Condensation forms when a surface drops below the <strong style="color: var(--text)">dew point</strong> — the temperature at which moisture in the air begins to condense into liquid water. On a cold winter morning, a standard aluminium frame can easily fall below the dew point, resulting in water streaming down your window frame and pooling on the sill.</p>
        <p>This isn't just an annoyance. Persistent condensation causes:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Mould and mildew growth on frames, sills, and surrounding walls</li>
          <li>Paint and plasterboard deterioration</li>
          <li>Air quality issues, particularly for people with respiratory conditions</li>
          <li>Structural damage over time</li>
        </ul>
        <p>A thermally broken frame maintains a significantly warmer interior surface temperature — typically 8–12°C warmer than a standard frame in cold conditions. This keeps the frame above the dew point in most realistic Australian climate scenarios, dramatically reducing or eliminating condensation.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 5 -->
      <div class="science-section">
        <h2>Acoustic Performance</h2>
        <p>Thermal breaks also contribute to improved acoustic performance, though this is largely a secondary benefit. The combination of factors in a thermally broken window — double or triple glazing, compression seals, heavier frames, and the polyamide break itself — results in a window that attenuates sound more effectively than standard single-pane or basic double-glazed units.</p>
        <p>Sound transmission is measured using the <strong style="color: var(--text)">Rw (weighted sound reduction index)</strong>. A standard single-pane window might achieve Rw 25–28 dB. A quality thermally broken double-glazed unit can achieve Rw 35–42 dB — a meaningful reduction in perceived noise, particularly relevant for homes near roads, rail lines, or flight paths.</p>
        <p>For maximum acoustic performance, asymmetric glazing (using two panes of different thickness, e.g. 6mm and 10mm) can further reduce resonance at specific frequencies.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 6 -->
      <div class="science-section">
        <h2>Energy Ratings & Australian Climate Zones</h2>
        <p>Australia is divided into eight climate zones under the NCC, ranging from Hot Humid Tropical (Zone 1) to Alpine (Zone 8). The performance requirements — and therefore the product specifications — vary significantly by zone.</p>
        <p>The Central Coast sits in <strong style="color: var(--text)">Climate Zone 5</strong> (warm temperate), with hot summers and mild winters. This means:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Solar heat gain management is important in summer — lower Solar Heat Gain Coefficient (SHGC) glazing or external shading may be appropriate for north and west-facing openings</li>
          <li>Thermal insulation still matters in winter — the Central Coast does get cold nights and the savings on heating costs are real</li>
          <li>Low-e coatings on the inner pane help reflect radiant heat back into the room in winter without compromising solar gain in winter orientations</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Getting the specification right for your home's orientation and climate zone is part of what we discuss in consultation. There's no single right answer — it depends on how your home is positioned, how much glazing you have, and how you use the space.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 7 -->
      <div class="science-section">
        <h2>Why Aluminium (Not Timber or uPVC)?</h2>
        <p>With thermally broken technology closing the performance gap, aluminium has distinct advantages over timber and uPVC frames:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong style="color: var(--text)">Durability:</strong> Aluminium doesn't rot, warp, swell, or degrade in UV. In the Australian climate, especially near the coast, this is significant.</li>
          <li><strong style="color: var(--text)">Slim sightlines:</strong> Aluminium's strength allows much thinner frame profiles than timber or uPVC, maximising glass area and giving a cleaner, more modern look.</li>
          <li><strong style="color: var(--text)">Low maintenance:</strong> Powder-coated aluminium requires essentially no maintenance beyond occasional cleaning.</li>
          <li><strong style="color: var(--text)">Recyclability:</strong> Aluminium is infinitely recyclable and the product typically contains a high percentage of recycled content.</li>
          <li><strong style="color: var(--text)">Design flexibility:</strong> Powder coating allows virtually any colour, and profiles are available in a wide range of configurations.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- Final CTA -->
      <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top: 16px">
        <h3>Want to Talk Through Your Project?</h3>
        <p>We're happy to walk you through specifications for your specific home, orientation, and climate zone. No pressure — just a straightforward conversation about what makes sense for you.</p>
        <br />
        <a href="/contact" class="btn-primary">Get in Touch</a>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>
